visit to a more tranquil and productive part of our village. To the very bottom left of our map, nestled beside the moat, you'll discover the flourishing Village Orchard. This verdant cluster of trees provided vital sustenance for the villagers. Imagine the bounty of fresh fruit harvested here each season – apples, pears, plums – contributing to the village's larder and ensuring a diverse diet. This orchard represents the self-sufficiency and agricultural ingenuity of the medieval settlement, a peaceful contrast to the fortified structures we've just explored. It reminds us that even within a stronghold, life thrived, sustained by the land and the diligent hands of its people.\n\nAnd with that, our journey through this captivating medieval castle and fortified village comes to a close. I hope you've enjoyed our tour and gained a deeper appreciation for the ingenuity, resilience, and daily life within these historic walls. Thank you for joining me today!", "labels": [{"number":1,"location_name":"Village Barracks","ymin":108.0,"xmin":81.0,"ymax":491.0,"xmax":477.0,"semantic_reason":"The large grey building with a roof and entrance, explicitly labeled 'Vistructurs Roof' and 'Primary Zone', representing the main barrack structure."}, {"number":2,"location_name":"Royal Armory Tower","ymin":105.0,"xmin":489.0,"ymax":860.0,"xmax":919.0,"semantic_reason":"The prominent golden hexagonal tower, explicitly labeled 'Royal Armory Tower', indicating a key defensive and storage structure."}, {"number":3,"location_name":"Village Market Square","ymin":859.0,"xmin":504.0,"ymax":919.0,"xmax":919.0,"semantic_reason":"The large, open, stone-colored ground area situated in front of the Royal Armory Tower and to the right of the moat, visually suitable for a gathering or market place."}, {"number":4,"location_name":"Castle Moat Segment","ymin":472.0,"xmin":102.0,"ymax":792.0,"xmax":736.0,"semantic_reason":"The large, blue body of water, visually resembling a moat, and implicitly labeled '