INFO:tools.adk_tools:Content of vision_proposal: {'script': 'Welcome, noble adventurers, to our grand tour of this magnificent medieval castle and its bustling fortified village! I am absolutely thrilled to be your guide today as we uncover the secrets and stories etched into every stone and landscape of this historic site. Prepare to be transported back in time, imagining the knights, merchants, and villagers who once roamed these very grounds. Our journey begins right here, in a place central to the village\'s everyday life and defense.\n\nLook directly before us, at that sturdy, impressive Village Barracks Roof. This formidable grey structure, with its robust slate tiles and the charming turret from which smoke gently curls, was once the heart of military operations and daily life for the castle\'s guards and soldiers. Imagine the clatter of armor, the drills in the courtyard, and the camaraderie of those who protected these lands. The primary entrance, an inviting arched doorway at its base, would have seen countless soldiers march in and out, ready to defend the keep or return from a long patrol. This building wasn\'t just a place for rest; it was a testament to the village\'s commitment to security and order, housing supplies, training facilities, and of course, the brave men and women dedicated to the realm. The architecture itself speaks volumes of resilience and practicality, designed to withstand the test of time and siege. Take a moment to appreciate the intricate details of the roof tiles and the stout stone walls.\n\nNow, let us continue our journey, moving clockwise around our map, towards a truly dazzling sight that speaks volumes of the castle\'s might and wealth. If you look across the grounds, to our right, you\'ll see the towering and majestic Royal Armory Tower. Isn\'t it breathtaking? Its distinctive hexagonal shape and the gleaming golden spire that crowns it are unmistakable. This wasn\'t merely a decorative feature; this tower served as the primary storage and workshop for the castle\'s weaponry and armor. Picture master smiths forging swords, polishing shields, and maintaining the vital instruments of war that protected the kingdom. Its strategic height also offered unparalleled views across the surrounding lands, making it a crucial lookout point. The golden cap isn\'t just for show; it\'s a beacon of strength and prosperity, visible for miles around.\n\nFrom this vantage point, let\'s cast our gaze downward and slightly to the left, where the bustling heart of village commerce once thrived. I\'m referring to the expansive open area we\'ll call the Village Market Square. Imagine this vibrant space filled with stalls, merchants hawking their wares, and villagers exchanging news and gossip. This "stone plaza," as it appears on our map, was the economic and social hub, a place where everything from fresh produce to handcrafted goods changed hands. The lively atmosphere, the shouts of vendors, and the chatter of crowds would have echoed between the sturdy walls of the barracks and the imposing armory tower. It truly was the pulse of the village community, a place where life unfolded in all its colorful glory.\n\nAs we continue our stroll, let\'s direct our attention to the stunning natural defense feature just ahead and to our left – the serene, yet strategically vital, Castle Moat Segment. This beautiful blue body of water, shimmering under the sun, wasn\'t just for aesthetic pleasure. It formed a critical barrier, deterring invaders and adding a formidable layer of protection to the castle walls. Imagine the challenge it posed to any approaching army, its depths concealing hidden dangers and slowing down any direct assault. Beyond its defensive role, it also served as a valuable resource for the village, perhaps for fishing or even as a source of water during prolonged sieges. It’s a testament to medieval engineering and an appreciation for integrating nature into defense.\n\nFinally, let us round out our tour with a visit to a more tranquil and productive part of our village. To the very bottom left of our map, nestled beside the moat, you\'ll discover the flourishing Village Orchard. This verdant cluster of trees provided vital sustenance for the villagers. Imagine the bounty of fresh fruit harvested here each season – apples, pears, plums – contributing to the village\'s larder and ensuring a diverse diet. This orchard represents the self-sufficiency and agricultural ingenuity of the medieval settlement, a peaceful contrast to the fortified structures we\'ve just explored. It reminds us that even within a stronghold, life thrived, sustained by the land and the diligent hands of its people.\n\nAnd with that, our journey through this captivating medieval castle and fortified village comes to a close. I hope you\'ve enjoyed our tour and gained a deeper appreciation for the ingenuity, resilience, and daily life within these historic walls. Thank you for joining me today!', 'labels': [{'number': 1, 'location_name': 'Village Barracks', 'ymin': 108.0, 'xmin': 81.0, 'ymax': 491.0, 'xmax': 477.0, 'x': 279.0, 'y': 299.5, 'bbox_type': 'landmark', 'semantic_reason': "The large grey building with a roof and entrance, explicitly labeled 'Vistructurs Roof' and 'Primary Zone', representing the main barrack structure.", 'anchor_policy': 'center'}, {'number': 2, 'location_name': 'Royal Armory Tower', 'ymin': 105.0, 'xmin': 489.0, 'ymax': 860.0, 'xmax': 919.0, 'x': 704.0, 'y': 482.5, 'bbox_type': 'landmark', 'semantic_reason': "The prominent golden hexagonal tower, explicitly labeled 'Royal Armory Tower', indicating a key defensive and storage structure.", 'anchor_policy': 'center'}, {'number': 3, 'location_name': 'Village Market Square', 'ymin': 859.0, 'xmin': 504.0, 'ymax': 919.0, 'xmax': 919.0, 'x': 711.5, 'y': 889.0, 'bbox_type': 'landmark', 'semantic_reason': 'The large, open, stone-colored ground area situated in front of the Royal Armory Tower and to the right of the moat, visually suitable for a gathering or market place.', 'anchor_policy': 'center'}, {'number': 4, 'location_name': 'Castle Moat Segment', 'ymin': 472.0, 'xmin': 102.0, 'ymax': 792.0, 'xmax': 736.0, 'x': 419.0, 'y': 632.0, 'bbox_type': 'landmark', 'semantic_reason': "The large, blue body of water, visually resembling a moat, and implicitly labeled 'Castle Moat Segment' in relation to the tower.", 'anchor_policy': 'center'}, {'number': 5, 'location_name': 'Village Orchard', 'ymin': 700.0, 'xmin': 81.0, 'ymax': 919.0, 'xmax': 202.0, 'x': 141.5, 'y': 809.5, 'bbox_type': 'landmark', 'semantic_reason': 'The distinct cluster of green trees and bushes at the bottom-left of the map, representing a natural green garden or orchard.', 'anchor_policy': 'center'}]}
